ecessary. The user’s clear about avoiding direct reflection, and since creating a test in the library package isn't an option, reflection might be the only way.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering native image execution**\\n\\nI need to ensure that tests run under native execution by default. We haven't added a `NativeImageSupport` catch for `Class.forName`. In a Native Image, calling `Class.forName` for included classes seems to work well, which is a relief. But, I'm worried about whether a native image allows modifying static fields initialized at build-time. If `SimpleLog` is initialized then, can I still modify static fields? They seem mutable, but I wonder how this interacts with the read-only heap when classes are initialized. I'll need to inspect the method call to see if any issues arise with `getContextClassLoader`.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Assessing reflection and metadata**\\n\\nIf the field is null, it looks like `Class.forName(\\\"java.lang.Thread\\\")` is used, which might be tracked as a reflection call in `SimpleLog`, and perhaps this is already covered. I wonder if it requires native metadata or if the existing `SimpleLogTest` handles this. I need to check whether the metadata for `Class.forName` is necessary or relevant. It seems like dynamic reflection may occur if `class$java$lang$Thread` is null in our action, which raises more questions about native metadata.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating JDK class usage**\\n\\nI'm considering whether the JDK class is allowed in native code. If it's not, it could be unsupported. I see that the existing dynamic report, SimpleLog, has a Class.forName call covered which is helpful. I wonder if the metadata lacks reflection configuration? It seems I need to inspect the library reachability to clarify how things are functioning and ensure everything is compatible. I'm curious about these interactions!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_kX58f6Pu7n33Rk